modules.name: AWS.Polly
modules.comments:
Amazon Polly is a web service that makes it easy to synthesize speech from text.

The Amazon Polly service provides API operations for synthesizing high-quality speech from plain text and Speech Synthesis Markup Language (SSML), along with managing pronunciations lexicons that enable you to get the best results for your application domain.

declarations.comments:
Deletes the specified pronunciation lexicon stored in an AWS Region. A lexicon which has been deleted is not available for speech synthesis, nor is it possible to retrieve it using either the GetLexicon or ListLexicon APIs.

For more information, see Managing Lexicons.
declarations.title: deleteLexicon

declarations.comments:
Returns the list of voices that are available for use when requesting speech synthesis. Each voice speaks a specified language, is either male or female, and is identified by an ID, which is the ASCII version of the voice name.

When synthesizing speech ( SynthesizeSpeech ), you provide the voice ID for the voice you want from the list of voices returned by DescribeVoices.

For example, you want your news reader application to read news in a specific language, but giving a user the option to choose the voice. Using the DescribeVoices operation you can provide the user with a list of available voices to select from.

You can optionally specify a language code to filter the available voices. For example, if you specify en-US, the operation returns a list of all available US English voices.

This operation requires permissions to perform the polly:DescribeVoices action.
declarations.title: describeVoices

declarations.comments: Returns the content of the specified pronunciation lexicon stored in an AWS Region. For more information, see Managing Lexicons.
declarations.title: getLexicon

declarations.comments: Returns a list of pronunciation lexicons stored in an AWS Region. For more information, see Managing Lexicons.
declarations.title: listLexicons

declarations.comments:
Stores a pronunciation lexicon in an AWS Region. If a lexicon with the same name already exists in the region, it is overwritten by the new lexicon. Lexicon operations have eventual consistency, therefore, it might take some time before the lexicon is available to the SynthesizeSpeech operation.

For more information, see Managing Lexicons.
declarations.title: putLexicon

declarations.comments: Synthesizes UTF-8 input, plain text or SSML, to a stream of bytes. SSML input must be valid, well-formed SSML. Some alphabets might not be available with all the voices (for example, Cyrillic might not be read at all by English voices) unless phoneme mapping is used. For more information, see How it Works.
declarations.title: synthesizeSpeech

declarations.comments: Amazon Polly can't find the specified lexicon. Verify that the lexicon's name is spelled correctly, and then try again.
declarations.title: InvalidLexiconException

declarations.comments: The NextToken is invalid. Verify that it's spelled correctly, and then try again.
declarations.title: InvalidNextTokenException

declarations.comments: The specified sample rate is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidSampleRateException

declarations.comments: The SSML you provided is invalid. Verify the SSML syntax, spelling of tags and values, and then try again.
declarations.title: InvalidSsmlException

declarations.comments: Provides lexicon name and lexicon content in string format. For more information, see Pronunciation Lexicon Specification (PLS) Version 1.0.
declarations.title: Lexicon

declarations.comments: Contains metadata describing the lexicon such as the number of lexemes, language code, and so on. For more information, see Managing Lexicons.
declarations.title: LexiconAttributes

declarations.comments: Describes the content of the lexicon.
declarations.title: LexiconDescription

declarations.comments:
Amazon Polly can't find the specified lexicon. This could be caused by a lexicon that is missing, its name is misspelled or specifying a lexicon that is in a different region.

Verify that the lexicon exists, is in the region (see ListLexicons) and that you spelled its name is spelled correctly. Then try again.
declarations.title: LexiconNotFoundException

declarations.comments: The maximum size of the specified lexicon would be exceeded by this operation.
declarations.title: LexiconSizeExceededException

declarations.comments: Speech marks are not supported for the OutputFormat selected. Speech marks are only available for content in json format.
declarations.title: MarksNotSupportedForFormatException

declarations.comments: The maximum size of the lexeme would be exceeded by this operation.
declarations.title: MaxLexemeLengthExceededException

declarations.comments: The maximum number of lexicons would be exceeded by this operation.
declarations.title: MaxLexiconsNumberExceededException

declarations.comments: An unknown condition has caused a service failure.
declarations.title: ServiceFailureException

declarations.comments: SSML speech marks are not supported for plain text-type input.
declarations.title: SsmlMarksNotSupportedForTextTypeException

declarations.comments: The value of the "Text" parameter is longer than the accepted limits. The limit for input text is a maximum of 3000 characters total, of which no more than 1500 can be billed characters. SSML tags are not counted as billed characters.
declarations.title: TextLengthExceededException

declarations.comments: The alphabet specified by the lexicon is not a supported alphabet. Valid values are x-sampa and ipa.
declarations.title: UnsupportedPlsAlphabetException

declarations.comments: The language specified in the lexicon is unsupported. For a list of supported languages, see Lexicon Attributes.
declarations.title: UnsupportedPlsLanguageException

declarations.comments: Description of the voice.
declarations.title: Voice
